# =============================================================================
# Taktology — a minimal interchange vocabulary for takt / Lean production planning
# =============================================================================
#
# Purpose
#   A small, modular ontology for the PROCESS half of takt planning (wagons,
#   trains, takt tasks, crews, takt time) that sits on top of the TopologicPy
#   ontology (top:) for the SPATIAL half (zones, elements, geometry, graph) and
#   is aligned to IFC process concepts by annotation only.
#
# Design principles
#   1. Author only what top: / bot: / IFC do not already cover. The spatial,
#      topological and graph machinery comes from top:; this file adds tasks,
#      sequence, resources and takt time.
#   2. Align to IFC by skos:closeMatch, NOT owl:imports of ifcOWL. ifcOWL is a
#      ~14k-axiom monolith; importing it would defeat the modularity goal. The
#      ifc: prefix is used only as a resolvable target for closeMatch.
#   3. closeMatch is an INTERCHANGE bridge, not a reasoning bridge. It does not
#      license a reasoner to treat a takt:TaktTask and an ifc:IfcTask as
#      identical, nor to transfer properties across the mapping. Round-tripping
#      to an .ifc file is the job of a converter, not of these axioms.
#
# Status: v0.2.0 — adds takt:actsOn (direct task->element operand link).
# License: see LICENSE at repo root.
# =============================================================================

@prefix takt: <https://w3id.org/taktology#> .
@prefix top:  <https://wassimj.github.io/topologicpy/ontology/topologicpy#> .
@prefix bot:  <https://w3id.org/bot#> .
@prefix ifc:  <https://standards.buildingsmart.org/IFC/DEV/IFC4/ADD2_TC1/OWL#> .
@prefix owl:  <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdf:  <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix skos: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .
@prefix xsd:  <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Ontology header
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
<https://w3id.org/taktology> a owl:Ontology ;
    dcterms:title "Taktology — takt production planning vocabulary"@en ;
    owl:versionInfo "0.2.0" ;
    rdfs:comment """A minimal interchange vocabulary for takt / Lean construction
        production planning. Provides the process layer (takt tasks, wagons,
        trains, crews, takt time) on top of the TopologicPy ontology (top:),
        aligned to IFC process concepts via skos:closeMatch."""@en ;
    rdfs:seeAlso <https://wassimj.github.io/topologicpy/ontology/topologicpy.ttl> ;
    rdfs:seeAlso <https://w3id.org/bot#> .

# =============================================================================
# CLASSES
# =============================================================================

# --- The takt zone: a programme-grouped spatial region the work flows through.
#     A single subclass of top:FunctionalZone is all that is needed — it inherits
#     Cell + bot:Zone + the IFC zone alignment + containsElement + area/volume.
takt:TaktZone a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf top:FunctionalZone ;
    rdfs:label "Takt zone"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """A spatial work area through which takt wagons flow at a fixed
        rhythm. Often a half-floor, fire compartment or room cluster that does not
        align with a single storey or space — which is exactly why it subclasses
        top:FunctionalZone (a zone grouped by function/programme) rather than a
        structural zone."""@en ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcSpatialZone .

# --- The wagon as a reusable template (the activity-structure row): a trade's
#     work package, independent of which zone it lands in.
takt:WagonType a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Wagon type"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """The reusable definition of a single trade's work package — e.g.
        'Enkling gipsväggar', ~5 workers, 0.58 h/m². This is the TYPE level; its
        per-zone occurrences are takt:TaktTask instances linked by
        takt:instantiates."""@en ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcTaskType .

# --- The takt task: one occurrence = one wagon in one zone (one cell of the grid).
takt:TaktTask a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Takt task"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """A concrete occurrence of a wagon performed in one takt zone for
        one takt (one coloured cell of the production plan). Carries its own takt
        time and acts on a specific subset of the zone's elements."""@en ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcTask .

# --- The crew / gang performing the work (the Dexx codes in the LUMI sheet).
takt:Crew a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Crew"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "A labour resource (gang) that performs takt tasks."@en ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcCrewResource .

# --- The timing payload of a task.
takt:TaktTime a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Takt time"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """The schedule payload of a takt task: takt slot, planned
        duration (typically the fixed takt, e.g. P1W), start and finish."""@en ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcTaskTime .

# --- The train: the ordered convoy of wagons. NOT a single IFC entity — it is a
#     PATH through the task graph, so it subclasses top:Path. (Reading A; see notes.)
takt:Train a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf top:Path ;
    rdfs:label "Train"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """An ordered sequence of takt tasks — the convoy of trades that
        marches through a zone back-to-back (Reading A). Modelled as a top:Path
        because a train is an ordered traversal of the task graph, not a first-class
        entity. The ordering is carried by the takt:hasSuccessor chain."""@en .

# =============================================================================
# OBJECT PROPERTIES  (the glue top:/IFC do not give you)
# =============================================================================

# --- occurrence -> template
takt:instantiates a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "instantiates"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Links a takt task occurrence to the wagon type it realises."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  takt:WagonType ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcRelDefinesByType .

# --- task -> WHERE it happens (location sense of IfcRelAssignsToProduct)
takt:performedIn a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "performed in"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """The takt zone a task is located in. This is the LOCATION sense
        of IfcRelAssignsToProduct (RelatingProduct = a spatial element). It is the
        work AREA, which generally contains elements for several trades — not only
        the ones this task acts on. For the operand, use takt:actsOn."""@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  top:FunctionalZone ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcRelAssignsToProduct .

# --- task -> WHAT it acts on  (operand sense of IfcRelAssignsToProduct)   [v0.2.0]
takt:actsOn a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "acts on"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """The building element(s) this task constructs, installs, or
        operates on — the OPERAND of the work, distinct from the zone it is located
        in (takt:performedIn). This is the link 4D-BIM practice draws directly from
        IfcTask to IfcBuiltElement via IfcRelAssignsToProduct. It is a SUBSET of the
        zone's containsElement inventory, and it — not the zone total — is what the
        quantity-to-duration formula should sum over. Note this property is
        deliberately broader than IFC's 'resulting product' framing: it covers both
        elements PRODUCED by the task (e.g. a wall built by drywall) and pre-existing
        elements OPERATED ON by the task (e.g. a wall painted)."""@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  top:Element ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcRelAssignsToProduct .

# --- task -> crew
takt:performedBy a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "performed by"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "The crew that performs the takt task."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  takt:Crew ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcRelAssignsToProcess .

# --- sequence (this chain IS the train)
takt:hasSuccessor a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has successor"@en ;
    rdfs:comment """The next takt task in execution order. The chain of these edges
        is the train. Maps to IfcRelSequence, which additionally carries SequenceType
        and lag — richer than this simple pointer; add those as edge data if needed."""@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  takt:TaktTask ;
    skos:closeMatch ifc:IfcRelSequence .

takt:hasPredecessor a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has predecessor"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Inverse of takt:hasSuccessor."@en ;
    owl:inverseOf takt:hasSuccessor ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  takt:TaktTask .

# --- task -> its timing payload
takt:hasTaktTime a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has takt time"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Links a takt task to its TaktTime schedule payload."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  takt:TaktTime .

# --- train -> member tasks
takt:hasMember a owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has member"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Associates a train with the takt tasks that compose it."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:Train ;
    rdfs:range  takt:TaktTask .

# =============================================================================
# DATATYPE PROPERTIES  (the takt-specific values with no home in top:)
# =============================================================================

takt:productionRate a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "production rate"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Effort value in person-hours per unit, e.g. h/m² (BIMTakt)."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:WagonType ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:decimal .

takt:crewSize a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "crew size"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Number of workers per column (MA/Kol)."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:WagonType ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:integer .

takt:quantityUnit a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "quantity unit"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "What the wagon's quantity is measured in: AREA | VOLUME | COUNT. Selects which geometric quantity the duration formula reads."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:WagonType ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:string .

takt:crewCode a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "crew code"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Discipline/gang code, e.g. 'DE14'."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:Crew ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:string .

takt:slot a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "takt slot"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "The takt slot the task is scheduled in (e.g. week number)."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTime ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:integer .

takt:duration a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "duration"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "ISO 8601 duration, e.g. 'P1W' for a one-week takt."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTime ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:duration .

takt:start a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "start"@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTime ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:date .

takt:finish a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "finish"@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTime ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:date .

takt:isMilestone a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "is milestone"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "TRUE for milestone tasks (e.g. 'Inflytt HG01', 'Dem. bygghiss')."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktTask ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:boolean .

takt:plan a owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "plan"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Storey grouping label for a takt zone, e.g. 'PLAN 5'."@en ;
    rdfs:domain takt:TaktZone ;
    rdfs:range  xsd:string .

# =============================================================================
# NOTES FOR IMPLEMENTERS
# =============================================================================
# 1. NAMESPACE. https://w3id.org/taktology# is the intended permanent namespace
#    but the w3id.org redirect must be registered before publishing. Until then
#    treat it as a placeholder; do not assume it resolves.
#
# 2. top: NAMESPACE. Verify the exact TopologicPy ontology namespace URI against
#    the published file (https://wassimj.github.io/topologicpy/ontology/topologicpy.ttl)
#    before relying on top:FunctionalZone / top:Element / top:Path / top:area /
#    top:volume / top:containsElement. The URI used here is the expected form.
#
# 3. DURATION IS COMPUTED, NOT ASSERTED. duration on TaktTime is normally derived:
#       qty   = sum( e.area  for e in task.actsOn )   # or e.volume, per quantityUnit
#       hours = qty * wagonType.productionRate
#       days  = hours / (wagonType.crewSize * HOURS_PER_DAY)
#    Read the quantity from takt:actsOn (the operand subset), NOT from the zone
#    total via performedIn -> containsElement — otherwise every trade in the zone
#    inherits the same quantity, which is wrong.
#
# 4. TRAIN READING A vs B. takt:Train + the hasSuccessor chain encode Reading A
#    (cross-trade convoy through one zone). For Reading B (one wagon's run across
#    zones), put hasSuccessor edges between same-wagon occurrences in adjacent
#    zones instead. Pin this down with the team before generating instances.
#
# 5. closeMatch, NOT equivalentClass. Do not strengthen any skos:closeMatch to
#    owl:equivalentClass without verifying the IFC entity and the takt term are
#    genuinely identical in cardinality and semantics. performedIn and actsOn both
#    closeMatch IfcRelAssignsToProduct on purpose — mirroring IFC's own overloading
#    of that relationship for location vs operand.
# =============================================================================
